3 - Overview of USBGuard Commands

USBGuard is a command-line tool used to manage USB device authorization on Linux systems. Below are the key commands you can use with USBGuard.
Key Commands
Command	Description
usbguard list-devices	Lists all USB devices recognized by USBGuard.
usbguard allow-device <id>	Authorizes a specific USB device to interact with the system.
usbguard block-device <id>	Deauthorizes a specific USB device, preventing it from interacting with the system.
usbguard reject-device <id>	Deauthorizes and removes a specific USB device from the system.
usbguard generate-policy	Creates an initial policy based on currently connected USB devices.
usbguard append-rule <rule>	Adds a new rule to the existing policy.
usbguard remove-rule <id>	Removes a specific rule from the policy.
Additional Information

    Listing Devices: Use usbguard list-devices to see all devices currently recognized by the system. This command helps you identify which devices are available for authorization or blocking.

    Authorizing Devices: To allow a device, replace <id> with the device's ID in the command usbguard allow-device <id>. This action permits the device to communicate with the system.

    Deauthorizing Devices: The commands usbguard block-device <id> and usbguard reject-device <id> are used to prevent devices from interacting with the system. The difference is that block-device temporarily stops communication, while reject-device removes the device from the system's recognition.

